17 PART V. METROPOLITAN PUBLIC TRANSPORTATION AUTHORITY
18 SECTION 5.1. Chapter 160A of the General Statutes is amended by adding a new
19 Article to read:
20 "Article 34.
21 "Metropolitan Public Transportation Authority.
22 "§ 160A-900. Title.
23 This Article shall be known and may be cited as the "Metropolitan Public Transportation
24 Authority Act."
25 "§ 160A-901. Definitions.
26 As used in this Article, unless the context otherwise requires:
27 (1) Authority. – A metropolitan public transportation authority as defined by
28 subdivision (5) of this section.
29 (2) Board of trustees. – The governing board of the authority, in which the general
30 legislative powers of the authority are vested.
31 (3) Metropolitan public transportation authority. – A body corporate and politic
32 organized in accordance with the provisions of this Article for the purposes,
33 with the powers and subject to the restrictions hereinafter set forth.
34 (4) Population. – The number of persons residing in respective areas as defined
35 and enumerated in the most recent decennial federal census.
36 (5) Public transportation system. – Defined in G.S. 105-506.1.
37 (6) Unit of local government. – Any county, city, town, or municipality of this
38 State, and any other political subdivision, public corporation, authority, or
39 district in this State, which is or may be authorized by law to acquire, establish,
40 construct, enlarge, improve, maintain, own, and operate public transportation
41 systems.
42 (7) Unit of local government's chief administrative official. – The county
43 manager, city manager, town manager, or other person by whatever title, in
44 whom the responsibility for the unit of local government's administrative
45 duties is vested.
46 "§ 160A-902. Definition of territorial jurisdiction of authority.
47 An authority may be created for any area of the State that, at the time of creation of the
48 authority, meets all of the following criteria:
49 (1) The area consists of a single county that has a population greater than
50 1,000,000.
51 (2) The county borders another state.
Page 2 Senate Bill 584-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (3) The county includes at least one unit of local government that operates a light
2 rail system.
3 "§ 160A-903. Creation of authority.
4 (a) The Board of Commissioners of a county for which an authority may be created as
5 defined in G.S. 160A-902 may by resolution signify its determination to organize an authority
6 under the provisions of this Article. The resolution shall be adopted after a public hearing thereon,
7 notice of which hearing shall be given by publication at least once, not less than 10 days prior to
8 the date fixed for such hearing, in a newspaper having a general circulation in the county. The
9 notice shall contain a brief statement of the substance of the proposed resolution, shall set forth
10 the proposed articles of incorporation of the authority, and shall state the time and place of the
11 public hearing to be held thereof. No county shall be required to make any other publication of
12 such resolution under the provisions of any other law.
13 (b) Each such resolution shall include articles of incorporation which shall set forth all of
14 the following:
15 (1) The name of the authority.
16 (2) A statement that the authority is organized under this Article.
17 (3) The name of the organizing county.
18 (4) A provision stating that an affirmative vote equal to at least seventy-five
19 percent (75%) of the membership of the board of trustees is required to amend
20 the articles of incorporation or to adopt or amend the bylaws of the authority.
21 (c) A certified copy of the resolutions signifying the determination to organize an
22 authority under the provisions of this Article shall be filed with the Secretary of State, together
23 with proof of publication of the notice of hearing on each of such resolutions. If the Secretary of
24 State finds that the resolution, including the articles of incorporation, conform to the provisions
25 of this Article and that the notices of hearing were properly published, the Secretary shall file the
26 resolutions and proofs of publication and shall issue a certificate of incorporation under the seal
27 of the State and shall record the same in an appropriate book of record. The issuance of a
28 certificate of incorporation by the Secretary of State constitutes the authority a public body and
29 body politic and corporate of the State of North Carolina. The certificate of incorporation is
30 conclusive evidence of the fact that the authority has been duly created and established under the
31 provisions of this Article.
32 (d) When the authority has been duly organized and its officers elected as provided in
33 this Article, the secretary of the authority shall certify to the Secretary of State the names and
34 addresses of officers as well as the address of the principal office of the authority.
35 (e) The authority may become a Designated Recipient pursuant to the Urban Mass
36 Transportation Act of 1964, as amended.
37 "§ 160A-904. Territorial jurisdiction of the authority.
38 (a) The initial territorial jurisdiction of an authority created pursuant to this Article shall
39 be coterminous with the boundaries of the county that organized it.
40 (b) Except as provided by this Article, the jurisdiction of the authority may include all
41 local public passenger transportation operating within the territorial jurisdiction of the authority,
42 but the authority may not take over the operation of any existing public transportation without
43 the consent of the owner.
44 (c) The authority shall not have jurisdiction over public transportation subject to the
45 jurisdiction of and regulated by the Interstate Commerce Commission, nor shall it have
46 jurisdiction over intrastate public transportation classified as common carriers of passengers by
47 the North Carolina Utilities Commission.
48 "§ 160A-905. Membership; officers; compensation.
49 (a) The governing body of an authority is the board of trustees. The initial board of
50 trustees shall consist of 27 members, appointed as provided in this section. For each appointment
