1 below, the appointing authority may appoint an alternate that may act in the absence of the
2 primary person appointed. The appointments are as follows:
3 (1) Twelve members appointed by the board of commissioners of the county that
4 created the authority as follows:
5 a. The board of commissioners shall appoint one member as
6 recommended by the governing body of the municipality that has the
7 second largest population of residents that reside in the county.
8 b. The board of commissioners shall appoint one member as
9 recommended by the governing body of the municipality that has the
10 third largest population of residents that reside in the county.
11 c. The board of commissioners shall appoint one member as
12 recommended by the governing body of the municipality that has the
13 fourth largest population of residents that reside in the county.
14 d. The board of commissioners shall appoint one member as
15 recommended by the governing body of the municipality that has the
16 fifth largest population of residents that reside in the county.
17 e. The board of commissioners shall appoint one member as
18 recommended by the governing body of the municipality that has the
19 sixth largest population of residents that reside in the county.
20 f. The board of commissioners shall appoint one member as
21 recommended by the governing body of the municipality that has the
22 seventh largest population of residents that reside in the county.
23 g. The board of commissioners shall appoint six members in its
24 discretion. No more than one of these members may be an elected
25 official of the county.
26 (2) Twelve members appointed by the governing body of the largest municipality
27 in the county that created the authority as follows:
28 a. At least three of these appointments must be made upon the
29 recommendation of an entity that represents business interests in the
30 county. The municipality may reject a recommendation from the entity
31 that represents business interests. If the municipality rejects a
32 recommendation, then the entity that represents business interests shall
33 make another recommendation to the municipality with respect to the
34 appointment. This process shall continue until the municipality
35 accepts the recommendation of the entity that represents business
36 interests.
37 b. The governing body shall appoint nine members in its discretion. No
38 more than two of these members may be an elected official of the
39 municipality.
40 (3) Two members appointed by the General Assembly, one upon the
41 recommendation of the President Pro Tempore of the Senate and one upon the
42 recommendation of the Speaker of the House of Representatives.
43 (4) One member appointed by the Governor.
44 (b) Members of the board of trustees shall serve for terms of four years, provided that
45 one-half of the initial appointments shall be for two-year terms, to be determined by lot at the
46 first meeting of the board of trustees. Initial terms of office shall commence upon approval by
47 the Secretary of State of the articles of incorporation.
48 (c) An appointing authority may appoint one or more of its members to the board of
49 trustees, subject to the limitations of subsection (a) of this section. Service on the board of trustees
50 may be in addition to any other office which a person is entitled to hold. Each voting member of
51 the board of trustees may hold elective public office as defined by G.S. 128-1.1(d).
Page 4 Senate Bill 584-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (d) Members of the board of trustees shall have demonstrated experience or qualifications
2 in the areas of law, finance, engineering, public transportation, urban planning, logistics,
3 government, architecture, or economic development.
4 (e) Members of the board of trustees shall reside within the territorial jurisdiction of the
5 authority as defined by G.S. 160A-904.
6 (f) Every two years, the board of trustees shall elect from its membership a group of
7 officers, which shall include a Chairperson, Vice-Chairperson, Secretary, and Treasurer. An
8 election of an officer must be by a majority vote at a meeting where a quorum is present.
9 (g) No trustee may serve for more than two consecutive terms on the board of trustees,
10 but a person who has been a member for two consecutive terms may be reappointed after being
11 off the board of trustees for a period of at least two years. An initial term that is two years or less
12 shall not be counted in determining the limitation on consecutive terms. This limitation applies
13 regardless of whether the appointments are made by the same appointing authority.
14 "§ 160A-906. Expansion of authority.
15 Upon approval of authorizing resolutions by the board of trustees and the board of
16 commissioners of the affected county, the territorial jurisdiction and service area of an authority
17 may be expanded to include a whole county within this State that is contiguous to the then
18 existing territorial jurisdiction of the authority. Each of the authorizing resolutions must receive
19 an affirmative vote equal to at least seventy-five percent (75%) of the membership of the
20 applicable board. The authorizing resolutions shall contain provisions with respect to the
21 following:
22 (1) The date on which the territorial jurisdiction is to be expanded to include the
23 county.
24 (2) The extent to which the composition of the board of trustees may be amended,
25 if at all, due to the addition of the county to the territorial jurisdiction of the
26 authority. The authorizing resolutions shall not eliminate or amend the
27 requirements with respect to appointments to the board of trustees that are
28 provided in G.S. 160A-905. Subsections (b) through (g) of G.S. 160A-905
29 shall apply to any additional appointments to the board of trustees.
30 (3) Financial, legal, or operational commitments with respect to the county that is
31 to be added to the territorial jurisdiction of the authority.
32 (4) Any other matter determined to be relevant by the board of trustees and the
33 board of commissioners of the affected county.
34 "§ 160A-907. Voting; removal.
35 (a) A majority of the board of trustees constitutes a quorum for the transaction of
36 business. Each member shall have one vote.
37 (b) Each member of the board of trustees may be removed with or without cause by the
38 appointing authority.
39 (c) Appointments to fill vacancies shall be made for the remainder of the unexpired term
40 by the respective appointing authority charged with the responsibility for making such
41 appointments pursuant to G.S. 160A-905. All members shall serve until their successors are
42 appointed and qualified, unless removed from office.
43 "§ 160A-908. Advisory committees.
44 The board of trustees may provide for the selection of such advisory committees as it may
45 find appropriate, which may or may not include members of the board of trustees.
46 "§ 160A-909. Purpose of the authority.
47 The purpose of the authority shall be to finance, provide, operate, and maintain for a safe,
48 clean, reliable, adequate, convenient, energy efficient, economically and environmentally sound
49 public transportation system for the service area of the authority through the granting of
50 franchises, ownership and leasing of terminals, buses and other transportation facilities and
51 equipment, and otherwise through the exercise of the powers and duties conferred upon it, in
Senate Bill 584-First Edition Page 5

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 order to enhance mobility in the region and encourage sound growth patterns. Such a service,
2 facility, or function shall be financed, provided, operated, or maintained in the service area of the
3 authority either in addition to or to a greater or lesser extent than services, facilities, or functions
4 are financed, provided, operated, or maintained for the entirety of the respective units of local
5 government. An authority may take direct action to accomplish these purposes or may enter
6 agreements with another unit of local government in the service area of the authority or a private
7 entity to accomplish these purposes.
8 "§ 160A-910. Service area of the authority.
9 The service area of the authority shall be as determined by the board of trustees consistent
10 with its purpose but shall not exceed the sum of the following:
11 (1) The territorial jurisdiction of the authority.
12 (2) An area outside of the territorial jurisdiction of the authority provided that one
13 of the following conditions is satisfied:
14 a. If the area is within this State, the governing bodies of the political
15 subdivisions to which service is to be extended approve by majority
16 vote of their governing boards the extension of service into the
17 political subdivision or the purchase of real property within the
18 political subdivision for the extension of service.
19 b. If the area is in another state, the extension of service is approved by
20 any applicable federal or State agency and in accordance with the other
21 state's laws.
22 "§ 160A-911. General powers of the authority.
23 The general powers of the authority include all of the following:
24 (1) To sue and be sued.
25 (2) To have a seal.
26 (3) To make rules and regulations, not inconsistent with this Article, for its
27 organization and internal management.
28 (4) To employ persons deemed necessary to carry out the functions and duties
29 assigned to them by the authority and to fix their compensation, within the
30 limit of available funds.
31 (5) With the approval of the unit of local government's chief administrative
32 official, to use officers, employees, agents, and facilities of the unit of local
33 government for such purposes and upon such terms as may be mutually
34 agreeable.
35 (6) To retain and employ counsel, auditors, engineers, and private consultants on
36 an annual salary, contract basis, or otherwise for rendering professional or
37 technical services and advice.
38 (7) To acquire, lease as lessee with or without option to purchase, hold, own, and
39 use any franchise, property, real or personal, tangible or intangible, or any
40 interest therein and to sell, lease as lessor with or without option to purchase,
41 transfer (or dispose thereof) whenever the same is no longer required for
42 purposes of the authority, or exchange same for other property or rights which
43 are useful for the authority purposes, including, but not necessarily limited to,
44 parking facilities.
45 (8) To acquire by gift, purchase, lease as lessee with or without option to purchase
46 or otherwise to construct, improve, maintain, repair, operate, or administer
47 any component parts of a public transportation system or to contract for the
48 maintenance, operation, or administration thereof or to lease as lessor the same
49 for maintenance, operation, or administration by private parties, including
50 parking facilities.
