42 "§ 160A-912. Authority of Utilities Commission not affected.
43 (a) Except as otherwise provided in this Article, nothing in this Article shall be construed
44 to limit or otherwise affect the power or authority of the North Carolina Utilities Commission or
45 the right of appeal to the North Carolina Utilities Commission as provided by law.
46 (b) The North Carolina Utilities Commission shall not have jurisdiction over rates, fees,
47 charges, routes, and schedules of an authority for service within its territorial jurisdiction.
48 "§ 160A-913. Fiscal accountability.
49 An authority is a public authority subject to the provisions of Chapter 159 of the General
50 Statutes.
51 "§ 160A-914. Funds.
Page 8 Senate Bill 584-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 The establishment and operation of an authority are governmental functions and constitute a
2 public purpose, and the State of North Carolina and any unit of local government may appropriate
3 funds to support the establishment and operation of the authority. The State of North Carolina
4 and any unit of local government may also dedicate, sell, convey, donate, or lease any of their
5 interests in any property to the authority. An authority may apply for grants from the State of
6 North Carolina, or from the United States or any department, agency, or instrumentality thereof.
7 The Department of Transportation may allocate to an authority any funds appropriated for public
8 transportation, or any funds whose use is not restricted by law.
9 "§ 160A-915. Competition.
10 No equipment of the authority may be used for charter, tour, or sight-seeing service except
11 as allowed under regulations adopted by the Federal Transit Administration.
12 "§ 160A-916. Effect on existing franchises and operations.
13 Creation of the authority shall not have an effect on any existing franchises granted by any
14 unit of local government; such existing franchises shall continue in full force and effect until
15 legally terminated; further, all ordinances and resolutions of the unit of local government
16 regulating local public transportation systems, bus operations, and taxicabs shall continue in full
17 force and effect now and in the future, unless superseded by regulations of the authority; such
18 superseding, if any, may occur only on the basis of prior mutual agreement between the authority
19 and the respective unit of local government.
20 "§ 160A-917. Termination.
21 The board of trustees may terminate the existence of the authority by adopting a resolution
22 by majority vote to do so at any time when it has no outstanding indebtedness. The resolution to
23 terminate the existence of the authority does not become effective unless and until ratified by
24 majority vote of the board of commissioners of the county that created the authority. In the event
25 of such termination, all property and assets of the authority not otherwise encumbered shall
26 become the property of a unit of local government within the territorial jurisdiction of the
27 authority as specified in the termination resolution and, if accepted by the unit of local
28 government, the unit of local government shall succeed to all rights, obligations, and liabilities
29 of the authority.
30 "§ 160A-918. Controlling provisions.
31 Insofar as the provisions of this Article are not consistent with the provisions of any other
32 law, public or private, the provisions of this Article shall be controlling.
33 "§ 160A-919. Bonds and notes authorized.
34 In addition to the powers granted by this Article, the authority may issue bonds and notes
35 pursuant to the provisions of The State and Local Government Revenue Bond Act, Article 5 of
36 Chapter 159 of the General Statutes, for the purpose of financing public transportation systems
37 or any part thereof and to refund such bonds and notes and to refund any bonds, notes, or other
38 obligations of another municipality used to finance or refinance real and personal property for a
39 public transportation system to be owned or operated by the authority, whether or not in advance
40 of their maturity or earliest redemption date.
41 "§ 160A-920. Equipment trust certificates.
42 In addition to the powers here and before granted, the authority shall have continuing power
43 to purchase equipment, and in connection therewith execute agreements, leases with or without
44 option to purchase, or equipment trust certificates. All money required to be paid by the authority
45 under the provisions of such agreements, leases with or without option to purchase, and
46 equipment trust certificates shall be payable solely from the fares, fees, rentals, charges, revenues,
47 and earnings of the authority, monies derived from the sale of any surplus property of the
48 authority, and gifts, grants, and contributions from any source whatever. Payment for such
49 equipment or rentals may be made in installments; the deferred installments may be evidenced
50 by equipment trust certificates payable solely from the aforesaid revenues or receipts and title to
Senate Bill 584-First Edition Page 9

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 such equipment may or may not vest in the authority until the equipment trust certificates are
2 paid.
3 "§ 160A-921. Power of eminent domain.
4 (a) The authority shall have continuing power to acquire, by gift, grant, devise, exchange,
5 purchase, lease with or without option to purchase, or any other lawful method, including the
6 power of eminent domain, the fee or any lesser interest in real or personal property for use by the
7 authority.
8 (b) Exercise of the power of eminent domain by the authority shall be in accordance with
9 Chapters 40A and 136 of the General Statutes.
10 "§ 160A-922. Tax exemption.
11 The property of the authority, both real and personal, its acts, activities, and income shall be
12 exempt from any tax or tax obligation; in the event of any lease of authority property, or other
13 arrangement which amounts to a leasehold interest, to a private party, this exemption shall not
14 apply to the value of such leasehold interest nor shall it apply to the income of the lessee.
15 Otherwise, however, for the purpose of taxation, when property of the authority is leased to
16 private parties solely for the purpose of the authority, the acts and activities of the lessee shall be
17 considered as the acts and activities of the authority and the exemption. The interest on bonds or
18 obligations issued by the authority shall be exempt from State taxes.
19 "§ 160A-923. Removal and relocation of utility structures.
20 (a) The authority shall have the power to require any public utility, railroad, or other
21 public service corporation owning or operating any installations, structures, equipment,
22 apparatus, appliances, or facilities in, upon, under, over, across, or along any ways on which the
23 authority has the right to own, construct, operate, or maintain its public transportation system, to
24 relocate such installations, structures, equipment, apparatus, appliances, or facilities from their
25 locations, or, in the sole discretion of the affected public utility, railroad, or other public service
26 corporation, to remove such installations, structures, equipment, apparatus, appliances, or
27 facilities from their locations.
28 (b) If the owner or operator thereof fails or refuses to relocate them, the authority may
29 proceed to do so.
30 (c) Except as otherwise agreed, the authority shall provide any necessary new locations
31 and necessary real estate interests for such relocation and, for that purpose, the power of eminent
32 domain as provided in G.S. 160A-921 may be exercised provided the new locations shall not be
33 in, on, or above a public highway; the authority may also acquire the necessary new locations by
34 purchase or otherwise.
35 (d) Except as otherwise agreed, any affected public utility, railroad, or other public
36 service corporation shall be compensated for any real estate interest taken in a manner consistent
37 with G.S. 160A-921, subject to the right of the authority to reduce the compensation due by the
38 value of any property exchanged under this section.
39 (e) The method and procedures of a particular adjustment to the facilities of a public
40 utility, railroad, or other public service corporation shall be covered by an agreement between
41 the authority and the affected party or parties.
42 (f) Except as otherwise agreed, the authority shall reimburse the public utility, railroad,
43 or other public service corporation for the cost of relocations or removals which shall be the
44 entire amount paid or incurred by the utility properly attributable thereto after deducting the cost
45 of any increase in the service capacity of the new installations, structures, equipment, apparatus,
46 appliances, or facilities and any salvage value derived from the old installations, structures,
47 equipment, apparatus, or appliances.
48 "§ 160A-924. Reports to the General Assembly.
49 The authority shall annually submit to the General Assembly, on or before February 1, its
50 annual operating report, including a report of its administrative expenditures, and its audited
51 financial report. In odd-numbered years, the report shall be submitted to the Senate and House
