General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 Transportation Committees. In even-numbered years, the report shall be submitted to the Joint
2 Legislative Transportation Oversight Committee.
3 "§ 160A-925. Limitations on rail transportation liability.
4 (a) As used in this section:
5 (1) Claim. – A claim, action, suit, or request for damages, whether compensatory,
6 punitive, or otherwise, made by any person or entity against:
7 a. The authority, a railroad, or an operating rights railroad; or
8 b. An officer, director, trustee, employee, parent, subsidiary, or affiliated
9 corporation as defined in G.S. 105-130.2, or agent of: the authority, a
10 railroad, or an operating rights railroad.
11 (2) Operating rights railroad. – A railroad corporation or railroad company that,
12 prior to January 1, 2001, was granted operating rights by a State-Owned
13 Railroad Company or operated over the property of a State-Owned Railroad
14 Company under a claim of right over or adjacent to facilities used by or on
15 behalf of the authority.
16 (3) Passenger rail services. – The transportation of rail passengers by or on behalf
17 of the authority and all services performed by a railroad pursuant to a contract
18 with the authority in connection with the transportation of rail passengers,
19 including, but not limited to, the operation of trains; the use of right-of-way,
20 trackage, public or private roadway and rail crossings, equipment, or station
21 areas or appurtenant facilities; the design, construction, reconstruction,
22 operation, or maintenance of rail-related equipment, tracks, and any
23 appurtenant facilities; or the provision of access rights over or adjacent to lines
24 owned by the authority or a railroad, or otherwise occupied by the authority
25 or a railroad, pursuant to charter grant, fee simple deed, lease, easement,
26 license, trackage rights, or other form of ownership or authorized use.
27 (4) Railroad. – A railroad corporation or railroad company, including a
28 State-Owned Railroad Company as defined in G.S. 124-11, that has entered
29 into any contracts or operating agreements of any kind with the authority
30 concerning passenger rail services.
31 (b) Contracts Allocating Financial Responsibility Authorized. – The authority may
32 contract with any railroad to allocate financial responsibility for passenger rail services claims,
33 including, but not limited to, the execution of indemnity agreements, notwithstanding any other
34 statutory, common law, public policy, or other prohibition against same, and regardless of the
35 nature of the claim or the conduct giving rise to such claim.
36 (c) Insurance Required. –
37 (1) If the authority enters into any contract authorized by subsection (b) of this
38 section, the contract shall require the authority to secure and maintain, upon
39 and after the commencement of the operation of trains by or on behalf of the
40 authority, a liability insurance policy covering the liability of the parties to the
41 contract, a State-Owned Railroad Company as defined in G.S. 124-11 that
42 owns or claims an interest in any real property subject to the contract, and any
43 operating rights railroad for all claims for property damage, personal injury,
44 bodily injury, and death arising out of or related to passenger rail services. The
45 policy shall name the parties to the contract, a State-Owned Railroad
46 Company as defined in G.S. 124-11 that owns or claims an interest in any real
47 property subject to the contract, and any operating rights railroad as named
48 insureds and shall have policy limits of not less than two hundred million
49 dollars ($200,000,000) per single accident or incident, and may include a
50 self-insured retention in an amount of not more than five million dollars
51 ($5,000,000).
Senate Bill 584-First Edition Page 11

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (2) If the authority does not enter into any contract authorized by subsection (b)
2 of this section, upon and after the commencement of the operation of trains by
3 or on behalf of the authority, the authority shall secure and maintain a liability
4 insurance policy, with policy limits and a self-insured retention consistent
5 with subdivision (1) of this subsection, for all claims for property damage,
6 personal injury, bodily injury, and death arising out of or related to passenger
7 rail services.
8 (d) Liability Limit. – The aggregate liability of the authority, the parties to the contract
9 or contracts authorized by subsection (b) of this section, a State-Owned Railroad Company as
10 defined in G.S. 124-11, and any operating rights railroad for all claims arising from a single
11 accident or incident related to passenger rail services for property damage, personal injury, bodily
12 injury, and death is limited to two hundred million dollars ($200,000,000) per single accident or
13 incident or to any proceeds available under any insurance policy secured pursuant to subsection
14 (c) of this section, whichever is greater.
15 (e) Effect on Other Laws. – This section shall not affect the damages that may be
16 recovered under the Federal Employers' Liability Act, 45 U.S.C. § 51, et seq., (1908); or under
17 Article 1 of Chapter 97 of the General Statutes.
18 "§ 160A-926. Civil liability.
19 Except as provided in G.S. 160A-925, the authority shall be deemed a city for purposes of
20 civil liability pursuant to G.S. 160A-485. Governmental immunity of the authority is waived to
21 a minimum of twenty million dollars ($20,000,000) per single accident or incident. The authority
22 shall maintain a minimum of twenty million dollars ($20,000,000) per single accident or incident
23 of liability insurance. Participation in a local government risk pool pursuant to Article 23 of
24 Chapter 58 of the General Statutes shall be deemed to be the purchase of insurance for the purpose
25 of this section."
