1 27 of Chapter 160A of the General Statutes, or a metropolitan public transportation authority,
2 hereafter referred to as a "MPTA," created pursuant to Article 34 of Chapter 160A of the General
3 Statutes may approve the entering into of any contract for the purchase, lease, or other acquisition
4 of any apparatus, supplies, materials, or equipment without competitive bidding and without
5 meeting the requirements of subsection (b) of this section if the following procurement by
6 competitive proposal (Request for Proposal) method is followed.
7 The competitive proposal method of procurement is normally conducted with more than one
8 source submitting an offer or proposal. Either a fixed price or cost reimbursement type contract
9 is awarded. This method of procurement is generally used when conditions are not appropriate
10 for the use of sealed bids. If this procurement method is used, all of the following requirements
11 apply:
12 (1) Requests for proposals shall be publicized. All evaluation factors shall be
13 identified along with their relative importance.
14 (2) Proposals shall be solicited from an adequate number of qualified sources.
15 (3) RPTAs or RTAs RPTAs, RTAs, or MPTAs shall have a method in place for
16 conducting technical evaluations of proposals received and selecting
17 awardees, with the goal of promoting fairness and competition without
18 requiring strict adherence to specifications or price in determining the most
19 advantageous proposal.
20 (4) The award may be based upon initial proposals without further discussion or
21 negotiation or, in the discretion of the evaluators, discussions or negotiations
22 may be conducted either with all offerors or with those offerors determined to
23 be within the competitive range, and one or more revised proposals or a best
24 and final offer may be requested of all remaining offerors. The details and
25 deficiencies of an offeror's proposal may not be disclosed to other offerors
26 during any period of negotiation or discussion.
27 (5) The award shall be made to the responsible firm whose proposal is most
28 advantageous to the RPTA's or the RTA's RPTAs, RTAs, or MPTAs program
29 with price and other factors considered.
30 The contents of the proposals shall not be public records until 14 days before the award of
31 the contract.
32 The board or governing body of the RPTA or the RTA RPTA, the RTA, or the MPTA shall,
33 at the regularly scheduled meeting, by formal motion make findings of fact that the procurement
34 by competitive proposal (Request for Proposals) method of procuring the particular apparatus,
35 supplies, materials, or equipment is the most appropriate acquisition method prior to the issuance
36 of the requests for proposals and shall by formal motion certify that the requirements of this
37 subsection have been followed before approving the contract.
38 Nothing in this subsection subjects a procurement by competitive proposal under this
39 subsection to G.S. 143-49, 143-52, or 143-53.
40 RPTAs and RTAs RPTAs, RTAs, and MPTAs may adopt regulations to implement this
41 subsection."
